<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,311,264,290]" box="[189,311,264,290]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,311,264,290]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,311,264,290]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,311,619]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
Moderately small-sized (ca 2.0– 
<quantity box="[579,674,311,338]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
) malachiid beetles with the body subparallel and oval with abdomen not completely covered by elytra (
<figureCitation box="[727,852,346,372]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Figs 1–10</figureCitation>
). Colouration from yellow with brown bases and apices of elytra, to black with yellow spots on pronotum and elytra; lacking metallic lustre. Antennae dentate in females and flabellate in males, not long, reaching the base of the elytra; in males 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[204,215,451,465]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">st</superScript>
antennomere enlarged, sub-conic, 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[644,661,451,465]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">nd</superScript>
antennomere oval, half as long as the 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1135,1149,451,465]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">rd</superScript>
antennomere, the 3 
<superScript attach="none" box="[1384,1398,451,465]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">rd</superScript>
antennomere triangular, not wider than the 4 
<superScript attach="none" box="[714,727,486,500]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
, 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[757,770,486,500]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
antennomere wide triangular, with somewhat dilated outer edge, 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[343,356,521,535]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
with more strongly dilated outer edge, 6 
<superScript attach="none" box="[838,851,521,535]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
–10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[895,908,521,535]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
segments flabellate, cylindrical with long dilated outer edges, terminal antennomere distinctly the longest, curved at basal third, evenly rounded at apex (
<figureCitation box="[290,361,593,619]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[187,1398,658,861]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
Head narrower than pronotum, slightly elongate, eyes small, weakly protruding over the contour of head; frons and inter-ocular area flat and slightly impressed, glabrous, lacking depression or protuberances; clypeus slightly elongate, transverse, straight; labrum short and transverse; maxillary palpi short, ultimate palpomere thin, cylindrical, slightly narrowed and flattened apically. Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1239,1389,764,790]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Figs 2, 4, 10</figureCitation>
) transverse, with rounded lateral sides, not sinuate or depressed at base; scutellum small, rectangular, narrow, slightly transverse, with slightly subparallel apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[188,1399,899,1383]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
Elytra subparallel, weakly expanded posteriorly and not covering last segments of abdomen in both sexes; humeri indistinct and small; surface densely punctured, covered with light dense adpressed short hairs. Anterior tarsi (
<figureCitation box="[512,586,970,997]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) five-segmented, compressed, with a comb above the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1265,1282,969,983]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">nd</superScript>
segment, 2 
<superScript attach="none" box="[204,221,1004,1018]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">nd</superScript>
–3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[250,264,1004,1018]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">rd</superScript>
tarsomeres equal in length, 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[605,616,1005,1019]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">st</superScript>
is 1.2 × as long as 2 
<superScript attach="none" box="[850,867,1004,1018]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">nd</superScript>
, the terminal tarsomere slightly narrower and depressed, the longest, as long as 1 
<superScript attach="right" box="[602,613,1040,1054]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">st</superScript>
–4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[643,656,1040,1054]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
tarsomeres in anterior legs, 1 
<superScript attach="none" box="[1005,1016,1040,1054]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">st</superScript>
–3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1046,1060,1040,1054]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">rd</superScript>
in intermediate legs and 1 
<superScript attach="none" box="[1372,1383,1040,1054]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">st</superScript>
– 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[204,221,1075,1089]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">nd</superScript>
in posterior legs; claws thin, weakly curved and sharp, with dentate small lamellae at base; femora and tibiae simple, not swollen or strongly curved, lacking indentation. Metathorax weakly swollen, narrow, transverse, lacking appendages or tuft of hairs, but with specific straight and edged distal side, which is slightly lamellate. Pygidium (
<figureCitation box="[654,726,1181,1208]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) undivided, evenly rounded and narrowed distally, with oval emargination in middle; 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[549,562,1216,1230]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">th</superScript>
ultimate abdominal ventrite (
<figureCitation box="[910,979,1216,1243]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) strongly narrowed, bilaciniate, but both lobes narrowly adjoined, evenly rounded distally, with round-triangular emargination in middle and sharp lateral processes; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[642,712,1287,1313]" captionStart="Figs 1–10" captionStartId="6.[189,242,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,267,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-75@6.[219,1368,265,1849]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–10. Tonyattalus vanharteni gen. et sp. nov., holotype (SCH_ISEA_000133), ♂ (1–8), ♀ (9– 10). 1, 9. External appearance, dorsal view. 2, 10. External appearance, lateral view. 3. Left antenna. 4. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. 5. Left anterior tarsus. 6. Pygidium. 7. Ultimate abdominal ventrite. 8. Aedeagus, and tegmen, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6518293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6518293/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) elongate and strongly curved dorsally, typical of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Abeille de Perrin" authorityYear="1890" box="[1301,1394,1287,1313]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Attalini">Attalini</taxonomicName>
, with a long sharpened bristle in the inner sac in middle of distal part, tegmen wide, transverse, with thin short appendages.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="62" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,325,1423,1449]" box="[189,325,1423,1449]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,325,1423,1449]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,325,1423,1449]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,1469,1566]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
The new genus ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tshernyshev" authorityYear="2022" box="[388,525,1469,1495]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Tonyattalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[388,525,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Tonyattalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, is composed of two words, ‘ 
<emphasis box="[891,947,1470,1495]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Tony</emphasis>
’ 
<emphasis box="[966,981,1470,1495]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">–</emphasis>
nickname of Antonius van Harten, enthusiastic organiser and participant of the 
<collectingCountry box="[728,788,1504,1530]" name="United Arab Emirates" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">UAE</collectingCountry>
Insect Project, and ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1840" box="[1041,1125,1504,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Attalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1041,1125,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Attalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ – name of the genus, nominative to the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Abeille de Perrin" authorityYear="1890" box="[461,555,1539,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Attalini">Attalini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,345,1605,1631]" box="[189,345,1605,1631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,345,1605,1631]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,345,1605,1631]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Comparison</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[188,1401,1651,1924]" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">
The species of the new genus should be compared with species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Erichson, 1840" authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1840" box="[929,1198,1651,1678]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Attalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[929,1013,1651,1677]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Attalus</emphasis>
Erichson, 1840
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Champion, 1921" authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Malachiomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1208,1399,1651,1677]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Malachiomimus</emphasis>
Champion, 1921
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<emphasis box="[444,559,1687,1713]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">Nepachys</emphasis>
Thomson, 1859 from which they can be distinguished by a combination of the following characters: size small, ca 
<quantity box="[687,756,1722,1748]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
in length; the elytra abbreviated in both sexes and not covering abdomen completely; apices of elytra simple, lacking impressions; 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1123,1140,1756,1770]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="62">nd</superScript>
tarsomere in anterior legs of male with simple small transverse comb above; metathorax weakly swollen, with specific straight, edged and slightly lamellate outer side; aedeagus thin and strongly curved, ultimate ventrite with round emargination and thin sharp processes, the structures necessary to hold curved aedeagus during copulation, is typical of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Abeille de Perrin" authorityYear="1890" box="[660,754,1898,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Attalini">Attalini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,260,265,291]" box="[189,260,265,291]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,260,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,260,265,291]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Notes</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,311,724]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Tshernyshev, 2022" authorityName="Tshernyshev" authorityYear="2022" box="[318,455,311,337]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Tonyattalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[318,455,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Tonyattalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[462,569,312,338]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
includes two species known only from the Arabian Peninsula. Besides the nominal species, the other closely related species is 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wittmer, 1980)" baseAuthorityName="Wittmer" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[820,1157,346,372]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Malachiomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buettikeri">
<emphasis box="[820,961,346,372]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">T. buettikeri</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wittmer W." box="[976,1149,346,372]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" pagination="114 - 118" refId="ref11519" refString="Wittmer W. 1980. Fauna of Saudi Arabia. Coleoptera: Fam. Drilidae, Malachiidae, Prionoceridae (2. Beitrag). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 2: 114 - 118." type="journal article" year="1980">Wittmer, 1980</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, originally described as 
<taxonomicName authority="Wittmer, 1980" authorityName="Wittmer" authorityYear="1980" box="[222,751,381,408]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Attalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buettikeri" subGenus="Nepachys">
<emphasis box="[222,306,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Attalus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[325,440,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Nepachys</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[459,573,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">buettikeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wittmer W." box="[581,751,381,408]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" pagination="114 - 118" refId="ref11519" refString="Wittmer W. 1980. Fauna of Saudi Arabia. Coleoptera: Fam. Drilidae, Malachiidae, Prionoceridae (2. Beitrag). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 2: 114 - 118." type="journal article" year="1980">Wittmer, 1980</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
due to external characters of male, flabellate antennae and anterior tarsi possessing a comb above the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[779,796,416,430]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">nd</superScript>
tarsomere. Simple elytra lacking impressions and appendages in apices questions the generic attribution. Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Evers A. M. J." box="[929,1083,452,478]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" pagination="1 - 57" refId="ref10729" refString="Evers A. M. J. 1989. Phylogenese der Malachiidae (Col.) der Welt Kladistik und Biogeographie aus der Sicht der Pangaea-Theorie. Entomologische Blatter fur Biologie und Systematik der Kafer 85: 1 - 57." type="journal article" year="1989">Evers (1989)</bibRefCitation>
transferred this species to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Champion, 1921" authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1921" box="[316,718,487,513]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Malachiomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[316,507,487,513]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Malachiomimus</emphasis>
Champion, 1921
</taxonomicName>
based on the flabellate antennae of the male. This new combination is doubtful and confuses the systematics of the Apalochrini because of strong differences of a 
<typeStatus box="[251,302,558,584]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1921" box="[574,765,557,583]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Malachiomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[574,765,557,583]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Malachiomimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, occurring in Himalaya Mountains when compared with the Arabian ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1840" box="[409,493,593,619]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Attalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[409,493,593,619]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Attalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1921" box="[655,846,593,619]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Malachiomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[655,846,593,619]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Malachiomimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by its considerably large size (ca 
<quantity box="[233,331,628,655]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5-6 mm</quantity>
), wide, enlarged and transverse tarsal comb in anterior legs of male and simple pygidium; the body is elongated and subparallel, and the abdomen is completely covered by elytra, typical of Malachiinae-type species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[188,1400,764,1037]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">
After the revision of Himalayan and SE Asian species of the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Wittmer, 1966" authorityName="Wittmer" authorityYear="1966" box="[1020,1347,764,790]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Sceloattalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1020,1165,764,790]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Sceloattalus</emphasis>
Wittmer, 1966
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1921" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1921" box="[189,550,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Dromanthomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,428,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Dromanthomorphus</emphasis>
Pic, 1921
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Tshernyshev S. E." box="[566,800,799,826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" pagination="358 - 374" refId="ref11163" refString="Tshernyshev S. E. 2015 a. A review of species of the genus Apalochrus Erichson (Coleoptera, Malachiidae). Zootaxa 3941 (3): 358 - 374. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3941.3.3" type="journal article" year="2015">Tshernyshev 2015a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tshernyshev S. E." box="[813,889,799,826]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" pagination="389 - 405" refId="ref11208" refString="Tshernyshev S. E. 2015 b. Soft-winged flower beetles (Coleoptera, Malachiidae) of the Himalaya region, with notes on Apalochrini. In: Hartmann M. &amp; Weipert J. (eds) Biodiversitat und Naturausstattung im Himalaya, Volume 5: 389 - 405. Verein der Freunde &amp; Forderer des Naturkundemuseums Erfurt e. V." type="journal article" year="2015">2015b</bibRefCitation>
, 2016), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1921" box="[988,1179,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Malachiomimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[988,1179,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Malachiomimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered as a Himalayan endemic, so the presence of some species in the Arabian Peninsula looks very strange. The specific appearance with abbreviated elytra, of the so-called ‘Carphurinae-type’, is similar to species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1923" box="[221,385,904,930]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Carphuroides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[221,385,904,930]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Carphuroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the tarsal comb above the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[770,787,904,918]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">nd</superScript>
tarsomere allows this species to be attributed to the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fleming" authorityYear="1821" box="[313,458,940,966]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Malachiinae">Malachiinae</taxonomicName>
and compared only with representatives of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Abeille de Perrin" authorityYear="1890" box="[1065,1159,940,966]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Attalini">Attalini</taxonomicName>
. Formerly, there was no genus with characters compatible with the Arabian ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1840" box="[858,942,975,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Attalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[858,942,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Attalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’; therefore, a new genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Tshernyshev, 2022" authorityName="Tshernyshev" authorityYear="2022" box="[1261,1398,975,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Melyridae" genus="Tonyattalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1261,1398,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="63">Tonyattalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[189,296,1011,1037]" pageId="5" pageNumber="63" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is proposed and described above.
</paragraph>
